Feeding an obese child: no breakfast and some charcuterie for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with being overweight, 9% of schoolchildren are overweight and 5% are obese.
As recent research shows, children who are obese come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This again shows how important the environment in which humans evolve and the patterns around them are.
For example, the tables of obese children are 50% more likely to be filled with snacks than those of normal-weight children.
19% of obese people had fries at dinner according to the survey conducted with an awareness campaign "Obesity is not an accident"
In families with small children, sports are also not a habit, which is now the case for most schoolchildren - only 15% said that at least once a week parents find time for active movement.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was carried out during the last school year and involved 900 pupils from Czech primary schools.
This was the second edition of "Obesity Is Not an Accident", sponsored by the General Health Insurance Corporation and Unilever.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 students from sixth to third have signed up for this project.
One of the major factors causing a dramatic increase in the number of overweight or obese children is the lack of proper nutrition and exercise.
"Only half of the children surveyed say they eat, for example, five times a day breakfast - in this case - lunch - snack - dinner, which is a basic principle of good nutrition", says one of the results of the survey.
No breakfast and snacks at dinner.
Experts point out that healthy development requires a few basic things, such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of the students' families eat at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
And the worst thing that has been found is that one tenth of the population doesn't have breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis for a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that families with obese children were more likely to eat unhealthy fries.
Almost every student - not to mention the weight - drinks sweetened beverages every day (70%).
More than 40% of the children surveyed exercise regularly but for the parents it is half, only 15%.
You make your own food
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own food from options offered according to their own personal taste and opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy eating".
Among their favorite dishes are many cakes, meats, and sweets.
"The most alarming is the high preference for sweet lemonade", the survey results state.
For lunch, pasta took first place, right before white meat.
The children did not want starchy foods at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Health policy
The survey also showed that children are willing to change their habits from the moment they receive ad hoc information.
"In a control of a group of survey participants who had completed the questionnaire after the 'Obesity is not an accident' awareness-raising session, a strong desire to move towards a healthy diet was observed", the survey results state.
The most striking example was in the case of sugary lemonade, as children began to prefer drinking water.
The children most often checked the questionnaire for white meat and fish as the main dish and would reduce to sweet dishes and "knedliky" (a Czech specialty of bread or potato dumplings).
