How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered trips mainly to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists went on holiday to East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A big exception for the period 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime started to have a westward inclination and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that citizens of the socialist bloc (including Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
In the case of Czechoslovak citizens who wished to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, they needed an invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not permitted.
Travel agencies at the time also offered trips to the West, but you had to either wait in line all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good acquaintance" with the travel agency.
And even after that it wasn't won yet.
The currency deal that was the condition for traveling west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not, however, convertible and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the agreement of currencies (Western currency) to travel west.
The Czechs spent most of their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and cottages which the Czechs bought themselves and this custom continues to this day.
Since 1989, the Czech travel industry has undergone a major revolution.
Although until 1989 holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at their peak, the Czechs spent 4 million days abroad last year in countries around the world.
The great paradox we do not realize today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in the neighbouring countries in the West has led to a huge wave of short-term visits, particularly to Austria, Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not for long travel by plane to the west which everyone wanted to see at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel agencies would put Czechs to sleep in tents in parks because our income was not enough to pay for a hotel or a boarding house.
A typical feature of a Czech traveller in those days was to take with him his own canned food, sausage, etc. to save money.
Another important moment was the exchangeability of the Czech krone, which allowed our tourists to finally, after decades, be free to buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and the average wage have risen, which has caused another important moment around 1997.
As a result of the growing demand for travel, travel agencies have started to offer tours since 1997 with charter flights, which have been greatly reduced in cost by means of contracts compared to what was available before.
In the late 1990s the Czech Republic had visa-free connections with virtually all the developed countries of the world except the EU, which later facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of tourism after the revolution was when the first charter flight to an exotic country, Thailand, was arranged from the Czech Republic.
As every year, direct charter flights are taking Czech tourists to distant warm countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
That's over 100,000 Czechs visiting exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008 the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully enter the group of developed countries.
In 2008 also the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50,3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15 000 crowns per person on holidays abroad including the associated costs.
