UFO-optic swings, magnificent swimming pools in Budapest: Travelers to Europe can experience the blue wonder - and after sightseeing or a long walk - can rest their tired legs in gas-water baths.
One book shows which swimming pool can be the most comfortable.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip for the past 18 months, there was one item that should not have been missing from her luggage: her swimsuit.
Lying on her back in the water, she observed the artistically arranged domes, and swam against the Putten marbles that awaited her on the other side of the pool and did not fail to admire the meticulously restored Art Nouveau of these converted pools.
If she liked a covered pool, she would write down in her notebook all the interesting details about the type of construction and the history of the building.
More than 200 pools have been surveyed in this way by architectural historian Meder and she has presented them in her already published book "Badefreuden" - the municipal covered pools of Munich, the historic bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "Hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
She has conducted her "trips to the most exceptional baths of Central Europe" in 13 countries. Besides Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she has visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland and one city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia respectively.
The 46-year-old German is a true devotee of the bathing culture.
Meder explains that she doesn't have much interest in sports but she feels drawn to water in a totally different way.
It is irritating that swimming enthusiasts have to look at blue tiles and take in the stench of bleach while joggers can breathe the enchanting scent of spice forests or can listen to the joyful chirping of birds in the park.
"I once wondered why swimming pools must always be so ugly", said the Viennese woman.
"So I started a collection of beautiful baths".
The surface of the water doubly strengthens the architecture
A dip in a pool and the volatile sauna oils - the wellness factor in swimming pools is huge because all the senses are aroused, according to Meder.
And if the builders had put in a little more effort, swimming pools could be a real delight to the eyes: "Instead of a floor, there is a water surface in swimming pools".
"It is transparent on one side, but on the other side it reflects the beauty of the whole building".
All surfaces are optically represented in a double way: high vaults, multicolored tiles, spring tiles.
The small-format image volume "Badefreuden" is an interesting 190-page report on the history of architecture and culture in the historic oasis of well-being - it certainly makes you want to jump into the blue.
The collector Meder discovered some remarkable specimens during her research in Hungary.
Next to splendid wellness baths such as the 100-year-old Szchenyi Bath in Budapest, she found waters containing nitrate in a natural cave in the karst (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) as well as a thermal bath whose basins are filled with water containing alkali and (Vrosi Termlfrd in Jszberny) and located in a bottle-shaped building.
On the other hand, the heated outdoor pools of Switzerland and Austria offer spectacular views. While the roof of the Zurich bath offers a view of the whole city, the snow-capped Arlberg can be admired from an outdoor pool in St. Anton: The Turkish bath has a window from which one can watch the animation on the ski slope.
Perhaps the most extraordinary swimming pool design awaits swimmers in Lngenfeld: The Aqua Dome tztal looks like a UFO that just landed in the Alps.
In winter, steam rises from the three open plateaus, while in the background the tztal mountains rise to the sky.
The Alhambra in the Black Forest
The smell of bleach doesn't come from every pool in the Meder collection.
Many thermal baths give off a sulphur smell, from the rpd-spa in the Hungarian Bekescsaba a strong oil smell, which is hard to believe, to be in a healthy spa.
The smell comes from the therapeutic alkaline water containing carbon hydrogen which is almost black and its mucus sticks to your skin as soon as you slip into the pool - a special spa experience.
Iris Meder's search for beautiful swimming pools also led to disappointment. When she wanted to visit Bad Luhatschowitz, a free outdoor swimming pool in Czechoslovakia, she found herself in front of a barricaded area.
The bath designed by the architect Duan Jurkovic in 1902 was meanwhile closed.
Looking out the window of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she observed weeds blooming between the tiles.
She observed the opposite effect in a charming pool in the Black Forest: the thermal palace of Bad Wildbad.
The building has already survived three phases; not only are there elements of neo-Romanesque architecture that have been evident since its design in 1844 but also a Moorish Alhambra style hall added in 1900.
Since its careful modernization in 1995, the thermal palace has remained the favorite bath of the pool expert Iris Meder - and not just because she is from the Schwarzwald.
"It is already a beautiful achievement to merge so many different building styles into such a wonderful unit", says Meder.
With such a palace, diving into the thermal pool is apparently only a minor issue.
Agricultural speculation
The German bank examines in detail the speculation on raw materials
By Christian Teevs
Is the German bank giving up its commodity speculation?
According to SPIEGEL-ONLINE, Josef Ackermann commissioned a working group to investigate the consequences of speculation for the world's poor.
In January, the group leader then wants to draw conclusions.
- What is it?
The Federal Republic's citizens are clear: According to a survey, 84% of Germans find it unacceptable that banks speculate on commodities such as corn and wheat.
Two thirds of those questioned even demand that the German bank and other credit institutions discontinue this business because it adds to the problems of the world's poorest.
This is the result of a Forsa survey of the order of the Foodwatch consumer organization.
The study is based on a report presented by Foodwatch in mid-October.
In this article, author Harald Schumann points out that stock market speculation on global commodities is driving up prices and that banks are complicit in the global famine.
The consumer protection campaign is in concrete alignment with the head of Deutsche Bank, Josef Ackermann, even if large banks like Goldman Sachs or Morgan Stanley are acting in the same way.
Speculation on commodities was initially introduced to protect traders from price fluctuations.
But the majority of experts meanwhile share the view that bettors have detached themselves from supply and demand - and are profiting at the expense of the very poor.
Ackermann reacted to criticism differently from his American competitors: he promised to investigate the complaints and said, "No case is worth putting Deutsche Bank's good reputation at stake".
According to reports from SPIEGEL ONLINE, an international working group is currently examining the accusations of Foodwatch-Report.
The review must be completed by the end of the year, after which the results of the Deutsche Bank Board of Directors must be presented - usually with a recommendation.
At the end of January, the Bank's President will indicate the consequences to be drawn.
This could lead to a reduction in the market for raw materials, or even a complete abandonment.
Ackermann building his image
Foodwatch chief Thilo Bode welcomed the news, but at the same time confirmed his criticism of the financial sector: "Speculation on rising food prices shows in a particularly draconian way how badly the banks today harm the public interest".
Ackermann is the first banking lobby to be particularly obliged today.
"Deutsche Bank must remove from its portfolio all investments for which money has been invested in food speculation", Bode said.
"It does not matter to Mr Ackermann whether it is a question of starving people or whether the reputation of Deutsche Bank is at stake".
Ackermann's awareness may seem surprising at first glance, but it is clear that the CEO of the group wants to present a perfect image, a few months before leaving office.
Deutsche Bank announced on Monday that the Chairman of the Board of Directors will not change anything in the Board's plans.
It could improve its brand image by abandoning controversial agricultural speculation.
And as for any losses, he has little to worry about - his successor will.
One in two would cancel investments in commodities.
Foodwatch is trying to keep a heavy hold on the manager.
So far more than 30,000 Internet users have already participated in the organization's campaign.
Bode published the survey on Tuesday, with which the Forsa Institute carried out questionnaires on 7 and 8 November with 1001 people.
Only 11 per cent found it legitimate that Deutsche Bank offers investments for which bets on food prices are made.
Many of the bank's customers would also be personally affected if they learned that their bank was involved in such transactions: one in two would, according to the survey, cancel all investments where money is injected into commodity speculation.
43 per cent would not recommend such a bank to their neighbours, 49 per cent said they would consider closing their account to change bank.
21st house in Vienna
The Pavilion That Moved
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with ups and downs and a happy ending: the Austrian pavilion for the Brussels World Exhibition in 1958 won prizes, was a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then fell into ruin.
Now it is open again and serves as an exhibition hall.
If one is enthusiastic about modern postwar architecture, its clear forms, its glass hangars, its bold and bold movements and its new building materials which are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of the Austrian architect Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 Brussels World's Fair is a good and famous example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion was once awarded the "Grand Prix d'Architecture" for its lightweight, suspended steel and glass construction.
The construction is considered to this day as an important milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architects so famous, that he also built the Pavilion for the next Austrian World Exhibition.
With its legendary BMW four-cylinder house and adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion project as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the Universal Exhibition in the Swiss Garden at Vienna's South Station, was transformed, and in 1962 a museum of the 20th century opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to hang the artwork, so not a good environment.
However, it was used for as long as it was, until the new building in Vienna was given to the Contemporary Art Department.
Since 2001 the building has been empty and has been deteriorating.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name of "House of the 21st Century" and will in the future be used as a museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opened the first exhibition - a stroke of luck in every respect.
The new start was led by Agns Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Belvdre gallery in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, promoted an art historian to a considerable career among others in her youth as an art skater, later at Sotheby's, at the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum of Modern Art in Salzburg, she particularly carried out transformation work with politicians and monument protection, she obtained public funds and private sponsorship and established the operation of it.
Except for contemporary art, works by the sculptor Fritz Wotruba, whose foundation bears the same name, were exhibited, a caf and a bookshop are located there, and an office is to be built there.
Strict supervision, low budget
Krischanitz was the ideal performer for the production.
Not only because he had sensitively transformed and expanded the Joseph Olbracht Secession and won the competition, but also because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and that for him the Pavilion was "an extremely important place" where he had seen "almost every weekend" exhibitions.
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost its generosity and lightness as a result of his move to Vienna and its change of use.
The current transformations have had major problems: the building was "an energy gap", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facades were changed, insulating glass reinforced with fibreglass was installed and the roof replaced by special safety glass.
The beams of the thermal bridges were reinforced or replaced, and the asbestos-filled roofs were repaired.
Two basements have made room for the new exploitation, a dim light panel between the house and the road provides lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - it's almost a new construction, but still the lightweight Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors remain, and the house is painted in a rust-resistant reddish-brown hue.
And the theater is even exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under the close supervision of the authorities responsible for monuments and with a small budget.
"Often good and cheap materials had to be found, and which also appeal to the monument protection office", says Krischanitz and he draws attention to a raw ground in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and transformations, the building remained flexible and light.
This would have been difficult with the Pavilion, "which came from Brussels", Krischanitz said recently, a typical "Drop-in-the-City" story.
Such architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken a good conscience".
But in this case the 21st century house is not in the wrong place, because if it is a lucky urban construction: around the Swiss Garden stands the newly planned "central station district" with offices and apartments.
And another stroke of luck may be coming: the 21st Century House could benefit from the reinforcement of another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the temporary art center in Berlin, and as is said, she is already negotiating with the city to get a site in the vicinity of the Swiss Garden.
