The Lake Zurich Bank Scandal
The most adventurous bank in Europe is not in Italy or France, but in Switzerland.
UBS almost went bankrupt in the financial crisis and has been going through one crisis after another.
A German must lead now.
It's certainly not what Axel Weber had imagined.
After his spectacular departure from the Bundesbank, it was announced in July that he would take up an almost equally spectacular position in 2013: Chairman of the Board of Directors of the Swiss bank UBS - a big step towards an unexpected and lucrative career.
Axel Weber publicly cheered, saluted Switzerland for its beauty and UBS for its newfound solidity and made friendly remarks about the future colleagues.
"UBS has passed the Turnaround".
"I look forward to working with Kaspar Villiger and Oswald Grbel".
And yet, as September came along, it was clear that everything was about to change.
A London-based UBS securities dealer had hijacked all the bank's security systems and stolen about 1.7 billion euros.
The head of the UBS board of directors, Oswald Grbel, a well-known banker not only in Switzerland, had to leave.
The chairman of the board of directors of UBS has since been considered ill - and everyone is asking: When will Axel Weber finally return?
We've already learned that Weber can be a bank advisor from February 2012.
And he will take over as chairman of the board as early as May - not in 2013, as the bank announced Tuesday.
For Axel Weber, this is getting difficult.
He's not a banker, much more a professor of economics and president of the bank, and he would certainly have needed a period of adjustment.
In a single stroke, he takes responsibility for the strategy of a bank which has just proved once again that it has long since earned the title of 'Europe's biggest scandal bank'.
Indeed, on the one hand UBS is huge - until recently it was the world's largest asset manager, and on the other hand it has been skating for years from one scandal to another.
Nothing, it seems, spared the proud Swiss bank.
It started during the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS had an excellent reputation.
The image of the quiet, solid, yet cunning Swiss asset manager was combined with ambitious goals: it also wanted to become a very large investment bank.
So UBS was managing on one hand in 2007 with $1.6 billion more money coming from a wealthy customer base than any other bank in the world.
On the other hand, it had advanced as an investment bank into the league of the world's largest banks.
It made an impression.
Former banker Hans Geiger, who later taught banking for many years in Zurich, recalls: "I always took UBS as a model of a good bank for my students".
"In the present light, you ask, how could I have been so wrong?"
He was profoundly mistaken.
In 2007 it became apparent that for the first time something was wrong at UBS.
In the middle of the year, President Peter Wuffli, who had been regarded as a top intellectual and a brilliant banker, made a surprising retirement.
A few months later we got a sense of why he had left.
The bank division had burst with sub-prime documents and had to cross over billions.
To support this, UBS announced a capital increase of 13 billion francs and put a cross on it.
It has indeed found investors, but they would have frowned on it not long ago: an opaque Asian state fund from Singapore and an Arab state fund, which was so overlooked that we never even heard its name.
But that was only the first blow.
In April 2008, things got worse.
The bank had to announce again billions in losses, and the chairman of the board, Marcel Ospel, who was still in 2006 the second highest paid board in Switzerland, resigned.
In October 2008 the disaster followed: UBS was in the financial crisis before the bankruptcy, due to its investment mistakes, and had to be rescued by the State.
The National Bank bought tens of billions of problematic securities from UBS, the Swiss Confederation gave six billion francs for bonds convertible into shares, for which it could become co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shocked - because it noted how dramatic it can be for a small country to have such large banks.
Finally, the total balance sheet of UBS 2007 was more than five times the economic performance of Switzerland (see graph).
"We have not been able to save UBS once again", says bank researcher Geiger.
After the first calamity, there followed the second.
Already a few months before, UBS had capitulated because of a tax dispute with America and declared itself ready to release data on the wealthy clientele, who had cheated the tax maybe with the help of the Bank.
In addition, it agreed to a payment of $780 million - in return for unjustified profits from these operations with an increased fine.
In this way, UBS has more or less published that it has helped to avoid tax evasion.
At the same time, it has lost something that has always been its capital in competition with wealthy customers: the prestige of discretion.
After the scandal, Swiss banking secrecy was no longer the same.
The Chairman of the Board of Directors and the Chairman of the Board of Directors withdrew.
And the exodus of the money from the customers.
In a few months, the bank had lost credibility in its two main business areas: investment banking due to bad speculation and asset management due to aid for tax evasion.
And as things got a little bit more calm, and as we thought, UBS would get away with it, this unfortunate story of securities dealers followed: one securities dealer blew 1.7 billion euros, before the bank realized something was wrong.
And we publish: with risk management in investment banking it still doesn't seem to work.
"The Adoboli case has shown that risk management has changed too little", says Martin Janssen, economist and professor of finance at the Banking Institute of the University of Zurich.
The chief financial officer of a large German bank is sure of this: "The problem with UBS is that it does not have control of the risks".
However, it was exactly the prudent idea with which the Swiss bankers had long since taken up their position, that of becoming the custodian of the great fortune of the world: not too great risks, but security for money - and the world might well collapse beyond the Alpine republic.
The treasuries of the Swiss banks had become a symbol of unshakable reliability, as Lindt and Sprngli are for a particularly noble chocolate.
The UBS headquarters in Zurich is still in line with the solid image of the Swiss private bank - it is only slightly larger.
The situation is already classic.
The Bank is headquartered at Zurich Central Station, which leads directly from the Central Station to Lake Zurich, which itself is surrounded by the snowy peaks of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are prestigious, and the rents for shops are among the highest in Europe.
Jewellers like Tiffany's are found here among the traditional Swiss shops as well as those of Sprngli.
For centuries, Swiss bankers have resided here, from the national bank to the palace of Credit Suisse to elite private banks like Julius Br.
We're going into the lobby of the UBS through a heavy door.
Inside, the walls are clad in marble, in front are thick leather chairs, and next to the bank's logo, a large label for "safe".
UBS knows what the customer wants here: security.
This idea of the Swiss bank has one day or another been thrown off the market - or betrayed by the two big Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, as the head of a small private Swiss bank finds.
He would rather not read his name in the newspaper, after all like all Swiss bankers he does business with both big banks.
UBS would have become far too big, he thinks - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons would have spread further.
The Swiss would have nothing to say.
"And yet they have long since adapted to the manners of the Anglo-Saxons".
It was the Anglo-Saxon investment bank that changed UBS, it made high profits and then the debacle: no European financial institution lost as much money in the sub-prime jungle as the big Swiss bank.
The disaster became apparent on October 15, 2008.
"This Wednesday the governmental coalition of the small country of seven million people has undertaken the largest rescue operation in the history of their nation", writes author Lukas Hssig in his book "The UBS Crash".
With up to about 68 billion francs, or 45 billion euros, politicians have agreed to save the big bank from bankruptcy.
How could this happen?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem mainly in the size of UBS.
In June 1998 two of the three major Swiss banks entered into a huge group agreement.
A bank was set up, which was already too big for the small Switzerland - and it kept growing.
What helped was that the two different predecessor banks of UBS had completed: one rich but lethargic bank with a strong focus on asset management in Zurich and one poorer but already more internationalised.
Suddenly, international investment banks had favorable access to a lot of money, with which they could turn a huge wheel.
Two names are associated with the rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, from 2001 to 2007 Head of the UBS Group, and Marcel Ospel, former Chairman of the Board of Directors.
"I always thought that Wuffli and Ospel were a dream team", says bank researcher Hans Geiger.
"Wuffli, the great, modest intellectual, who is very good at models and statistics, and Ospel, the intuitive, who made his way to the top with his banking education".
But Ospel would have trusted Wuffli to the end.
And Wuffli would probably have made a decisive mistake in the end: "He thought his models were reality", says Geiger.
"This is a tragic fall".
Tragic, perhaps.
One thing is clear: the exuberance came before the fall.
The UBS staff clearly remember the meetings of the executives at which the head of the Wuffli Group always uttered the same slogan: dethrone Goldman Sachs.
The American bank was the most powerful investment bank on the planet.
It commanded the "League Tables" rankings, which documented the success of banks at the time.
After all, UBS wanted to go all the way to the top.
He's already succeeded in some of these steps.
In the field of foreign exchange and securities transactions, it has played a very important role.
The company advisers, who were responsible for this, pointed out, however, a weakness: in international interest operations, in the banking jargon "fixed income", there would be a huge difference compared with the largest banks.
