Peter Englund's new book, "The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War", offers depth and generosity, and begins with a long list of characters that will warm your heart.
A tip to start with: rip this page carefully and make it your bookmark.
You will get to know these people in detail. In this romantic tale by Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during those few moments when, like one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the mists of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
Here he wrote an extraordinary book which he accurately describes as "a work of anti-history".
It contains a few well-known names, important treaties or famous battles; there is hardly any mention of an ambassador or discussion of strategies and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a "book describing what it might have been like", containing "feelings, impressions, experiences, and moods".
"Beauty and Sorrow" summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women on both sides of the war, from schoolchildren and botanists to climbers, to doctors, paramedics, and salesmen.
Some of them will become heroes.
Some will lose limbs, some will go mad, some will lose their lives.
Their lives here are like church candles, and as some are extinguished, new ones are lit.
Peter Englund's book is a departure from traditional history books.
It refutes the idea that the First World War was merely a terrible trench war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" is a skillful description of other war theaters - the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, and East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are under hives; one spends Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
War invades the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling of cordite.
When cannon shots are heard far away, and you're a stay-at-home mom, do you stay or do you run?
Who's coming anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts has been compounded by speculation, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors".
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German high-sea fleet.
Their stories are mostly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
The versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but they are best preserved by the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most of them deal with deprivation and the ability to cope.
In telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz".
"Switch coffee, fake aluminum, imitation rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons".
He's pursuing alternative food in Germany.
It describes "meat made from rice cooked in sheep's fat (and finished with a false wooden bone); tobacco made from dried roots and dried potato skins; wooden shoe soles".
It states that "837 permitted meat substitutes are registered in sausage production and 511 substituted coffees are found".
Some stories are about honor and courage.
One American acknowledges his own drive for savagery and says of war: "You feel that, after all, that's what men were meant to do, rather than sit in a comfortable chair with a cigarette and a whiskey in hand, reading a newspaper or a best-seller, and rather than pretend that such a varnish is synonymous with civilization, and that there are no barbarians behind your stuffy, nailed shirt.
A British soldier, on the other hand, realizes that he is in danger of dying, and that no one will notice or pay attention.
"When you're resigned to sacrifice, you hope to have an audience", he writes.
Unfortunately, it is more like "a man who is secretly strangled".
Other observations concern the decline of an old Europe and new forms of terror.
"Conflict is becoming more and more a story of economic competition", writes Peter Englund, "a war between factories".
He captures the arrival of what he calls "a new species in the early-century bestiary: the articulate, ideologically convinced mass murderer in well-fitted clothes, who carries out his butchery while sitting behind a counter".
People act unexpectedly, you find as much basic behavior as heroism.
Peter Englund tells of soldiers who tried at all costs to catch a venereal disease from prostitutes in order to avoid service at the front.
"The most grotesque expression is found in the trade of pus from gonorrhea, which soldiers buy and spread on the genitals in the hope of ending up in the hospital", he writes.
"The most desperate apply it to their eyes, resulting in lifelong blindness".
In this translation from Swedish by Peter Graves, Peter Englund's prose is flexible but not ostentatious, perfectly suited to his task as a human being.
In dozens of short scenes, he captures how the war "unleashed forces that were entirely uncontrollable: extreme nationalism, social revolution, and hatred of religion".
People are starting to wonder why their leaders are at war with them.
The best books dealing with World War I are often indirect, such as "The Great War and Modern Memory" by Paul Fussel, or "Nothing New in the West" by Erich Maria Remarque, rather than complete.
Peter Englund's work is an unconventional pantheon.
The ending of the book is the most overwhelming I've ever read in a non-fiction work.
I won't reveal it.
But it's like he's come out of his book, grabbed that page with the list of people in it from your hands and burned it with a match.
