Facebook is so full of personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site's advertising tool to find the people they're looking for with scientific accuracy - the way marketers have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett's team found that half a million members are fans of far-right groups in Europe, and they targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to take a survey, asking questions about their education level, their attitudes toward violence, and their optimism about their own future.
By connecting with these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without leaving the office.
"It's a new way of doing research", says Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not surprising at all: online supporters of right-wing groups are more likely to be men, young people and anti-immigration.
But surprisingly, "those who associate online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind their computer screens".
The DEMOS study is just one example of how Facebook has become the new must-have tool in the hands of scientists.
Think tanks, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all kinds of topics that touch on health issues and social trends, thanks to "likes", wall posts and status updates.
With over 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, the 'data supernova' is driving an explosion in search, increasing the number of research papers with the site's name in the title by almost 800% over the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you might not be able to approach on the street.
"Before, when you tried to conduct surveys on people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them".
"You were supposed to go to the party, but they would never let you in", says Jamie Bartlett.
"Facebook avoids all of this - you have direct access to their information".
Others say the site could offer a way to identify and treat health and social problems.
According to a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and her colleagues, young college students who talked about their drunken exploits on Facebook were far more likely to be alcoholics than students who kept quiet about it.
Megan Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to possibly help a student whose status would talk about alcohol too often.
