We also discover moments when Steve Jobs's perfectionism resurfaces, where he seems eager to hear Cringely's questions, giving him elbows to speed him up and move on to more important questions or topics.
Filmed before the days of Pixar, the iPod, or the iPhone, there's a curiously prescient aspect to Lost Interview where Steve Jobs evaluates what he sees as good and bad in other companies and shares his own vision for the future of computing.
It's one thing to read the posthumous career reviews of Steve Jobs, but there's something raw and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
He explains them and then applies them immediately.
Here's a quick recap of seven remarkable episodes from Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"All these years, I've always asked, 'Why do you do things?' and the answers have been the same: 'Oh, just because you have to do them.'"
Nobody knows why, nobody thinks deeply about things in a company.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs goes on to give details of his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Confused about how costs were recorded - often starting with a 'standard cost' assessed at face value and then adjusted with a 'variation' - he developed an automated factory that ensured the accurate calculation of commercial costs.
On the feasibility of playing the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the story of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that was used to hack into telephone networks and make free long-distance phone calls.
The device has been the subject of much written about before, but Steve Jobs' euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a pay phone, making a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
"We'd wrap the ball around different things about half a dozen times and you'd scream into the pay phone and it would come to you a minute later on the next pay phone", Jobs explains with a laugh.
"We were young, and through this Blue Box, we learned that we could create something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world".
We didn't know much either, but we were able to invent a little thing that could control big things, and it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Steve Jobs goes on to tell us about a wonderful trick that he and Wozniak devised: he telephoned the Vatican from the Blue Box in the middle of the night, impersonating Henry Kissinger and asking to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices leave in a frenzy of laughter just before the Pope himself is awakened.
On his love of technology (and Bill Hewlett's approach):
At the age of 12, while hunting for parts to make a frequency meter, he looked up Bill Hewlett's number in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs gets a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable influence on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my definition of a company and the way employees are treated".
Steve Jobs later became one of HP's employees to visit the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he discovered the "first desktop computer ever designed".
It was as big as a suitcase, had a small cathode tube, and I fell in love with it.
The teenager I was went back to HP and started writing programs for that machine.
On improvising innovation:
At several points in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products at a stroke.
Early in his career, while moving to sell some printed circuit boards, a client asked him to assemble a complete computer.
With only 30 days' credit, he had to take care of assembling and delivering the finished appliances.
Later, at Apple, he recalled the difficulties he faced developing a computer mouse:
"I remember a lot of arguments... people shouting at me that it would take me five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300].
And 90 days later, we had a mouse that we could make for 15 dollars and it was incredibly reliable.
On the big companies that are running out of breath:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had foreseen how many industrial leaders would go wrong and lose control of their market share.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, you make a better copier or a better printer, and then what?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company is not more successful.
Sales and marketing can make it evolve, so [these are the kinds of people] who end up running the companies and product personnel are left out of decision-making.
The product engineering that led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by people who can't imagine designing a good product versus a bad product - the manual labor required.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the '90s...
They took defeat from victory.
On innovation as an art form:
"A huge amount of manual work separates a great idea from an outstanding product... as you develop that idea, it changes and grows".
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are compromises to be made... some things you can't do, electrons can, glass, robots, factories too.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind by putting them together.
Finally, decisions are made on personal taste, and it's about trying to expose yourself to the best products that humans have created, and trying to bring those things into the product you're creating.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and great artists steal.
We're always ashamed of stealing great ideas.
That's part of what makes the Macintosh so special. The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who simply turned out to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn't for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another field.
Scalia and Thomas dining with health law opponents as the court convenes
