Pentagon's stern warnings about potential defense cuts
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta stepped up pressure on Congress on Monday, warning that imminent automatic budget cuts would undermine national security, triggering a financial chain reaction from the Pentagon corridors to the battlefields of Afghanistan, to the rallies of civilians.
The Pentagon is already digesting $450 billion in cuts for the next decade, but now fears that an additional $600 or more in cuts is imminent if Congress does not reach an agreement on spending.
"The impacts of these cuts would be devastating to the department", Panetta said in a letter to Senators John McCain, R-Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, R-South Carolina.
He said that the failure of Congress to reach a budget agreement resulting in what is called sequestering would result in 23% cuts as well as the freezing of many new projects.
"Such a large reduction, applied in this way indiscriminately, would render most of our ships and construction projects unfeasible - you cannot buy three-quarters of a ship or building - and would seriously undermine other modernization efforts", Panetta wrote to senators.
"We would also be forced to separate ourselves from a number of our civilian staff and, because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, we would almost certainly have to send civilians on unpaid leave in order to achieve the goal".
"These changes would shake the faith of those who support our military and seriously damage our preparedness".
The reductions could eventually affect the fighting troops, Panetta continues.
"While wartime financing of contingency accounts abroad is not directly affected by sequestering, the war effort would be negatively affected by severe disruptions in core budgets", Panetta warned.
"The contracting personnel would be reduced, leading to delays in contracts and oversight of contracts that support the war".
"Wage-management staff would be cut, leading to late payments to war suppliers, and legal and political support would be disrupted".
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days earlier, asking for details on the potential impact of automatic squeezing on the Department of Defense.
"The consequence of a sequester on the Department of Defense would have triggered a rapid decline of the United States as the undisputed world leader of military power".
"We are fiercely opposed to this draconian action", the senators said in a joint statement on Monday afternoon when Panetta's letter was published.
"It's not a consequence we can live with, and it's certainly not one we should impose on ourselves".
"Sequestration is a threat to the national security interests of the United States, and it should not have to happen".
Whether Panetta's letter and recent warnings from senators will increase pressure for a budget compromise or a call for the Pentagon to be exempt from cuts remains to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly virulent about possible cuts, even though he himself rose to the highest office in the Pentagon accumulating years of budget expertise in Congress and the White House and knowing he was faced with difficult choices.
At a press conference last week, the Secretary of Defense painted a grim picture of what might happen - a military with a shell, but no core.
"It's a ship without sailors".
"This is a bullet-free brigade".
"It's a fighter jet, without enough trained pilots".
"It's a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs that don't have enough trained soldiers capable of accomplishing the mission", Panetta said in his opening remarks at the Pentagon.
"It is a depressed force, ill-prepared and unable to face potential adversaries".
"Indeed, it invites to aggression".
In an addendum to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta specifically stated how further reductions could "generate significant operational risks: delayed response to crises, conflicts and disasters; severe limits on our ability to deploy and engage globally; and risk assumed unacceptable in future combat operations".
And Panetta said that some of the biggest defense projects could go to the cutting edge, including those already tested and some just in the early stages of planning.
This list included the Fighter F35 Joint Strike, a planned new bomber, the next-generation ballistic submarine, the new coastal combat ship, and the new field vehicle, which would replace the Army and Navy Humvee.
Stopping the development and testing of the F35 could generate $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but its supporters say it's a critical step in improving and responding to potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to Spot a Lie
A glance at recent headlines reveals just how pervasive deception and lying are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy swapping sexual harassment allegations with several women, each side accusing the other of lying.
Penn State administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly covering up reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught on an open microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies have destroyed careers and shaken nations.
New York Congressman and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner was made to look like an idiot by quickly issuing denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance violations related to the coverage of an extramarital affair.
And then, no one who has lived through history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton unleashed by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating on school and college tests are endless.
There have been cases where teachers have given test answers to students to make themselves look good on their performance assessments.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How many deception do we encounter?
Studies show that in any given day, you can hear anywhere from 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of them are utter lies.
Another study found that strangers lie to each other three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting each other.
Detecting or spotting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, say, charades, where the aim is to shout, "I've got you", cheat detection is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the last six decades at prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research on such projects, including in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars look you in the eye.
They don't always stutter, blush, or move.
Do not conclude that liars are hard to detect and hard to catch.
A trained lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, the micro-facial expressions, the form of the question, and the response time.
I've spent several years reviewing the vast body of scientific results and ever-emerging knowledge about deception, and it's clear that cheating detection is a modern skill that's easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating or managing.
Good liars are adept at reading others, making them feel comfortable, managing their own emotions, and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more "self-centered" lies while women tell more "other-centered" lies - usually to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but that the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you're perceived as a disbeliever, others will feel less guilty lying to you.
How can you tell if someone's lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
It's called "setting the benchmarks".
This helps to provide a reference point for measuring subsequent changes.
Watch your subject's posture, laughter, vocal quality.
You should know if someone is always moving his feet normally, so that you don't get unfairly accused when you see him moving his feet in the middle of the congregation.
Then look for signs of verbal and nonverbal deceit.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceivers can immobilize the upper body when trying to remember their story, they can point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or present a post-interview relief - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult questions have passed.
Interviewers often falsely indicate that the interview is over just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, be careful of your subject vocabulary.
The famous Scott Peterson slipped through the cracks using the past while pretending his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Deceptive individuals may also use distant language, such as "I did not have sex with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal cues are subtle.
One may use a lot of "wood language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to be honest... if I remember correctly... as far as I know".
This makes the answer perceptive rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing the skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone avoiding being victimized by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
