Climate adversity has slowed the economy
During the first year of the administration of Mario Lpez Valdez, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality increased, foreign investment decreased and the economy contracted.
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the Government of Mario Lpez Valdez, self-proclaimed of change, which generated great expectations regarding the advances of the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, the rise is not observed, in exchange there is a deterioration of the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures in February, apart from causing trillions of losses to the agricultural sector, limited the state economy's opportunities for growth, caused a contraction of economic activity in general by 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, justified mainly by the historic 31.16 percent decline in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the frost-affected report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there was damage to 582 million 835 hectares of crops, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 percent suffered partial damage, the main crops affected were vegetables, maize and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady rise in unemployment in the State, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the unemployment rate of the State during the first three quarters of the year an accelerated rise was observed, because while from January to March 55 thousand 053 Sinaloans were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the Economic Active Population, in the second quarter the rate is 5.28 percent and from July to September the average continued to rise to 6.19 percent, a rate that represents more than 74 thousand Sinaloans unemployed, an increase compared to the first half of 18 thousand 969 people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo Lpez Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the rise in unemployment can be explained indirectly in terms of actions carried out by public policy.
"What we're seeing is an increase in unemployment that is due to a variety of factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by legislation passed in Congress to fight money laundering, because for people who earn dollars illegally it's not easy for them to work for it, to invest it and use it in something", he says.
Migration in detention
Lpez Cervantes pointed out that the increase in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the state to work abroad in the United States has been restricted, firstly because of the difficulties of entry and secondly because when they enter they already have a lot of difficulties to find work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work, which causes unemployment to rise", he said.
Not serious
The analysis of the Sinaloan labour market is aggravated by the high level of lack of seriousness which predominates among the working conditions, according to the INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the employed population in this state work there without contributing as a worker to any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and lack of seriousness, another reason for the state's mismatch is low wages, the entity has the lowest salaries in the country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Provision.
