The Court Endorses "Analogue Cutting" in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analogue signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) rejected the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogue cut" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes needed to invalidate it were not gathered.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Caldern did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to bring about the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was rejected for not having reached the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, drafted by Minister Olga Snchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television is a statutory attribution reserved to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and the reservation of law.
Only Zaldvar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Snchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and by admitting the complaints, Minister Snchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions it envisages for the digital transition.
The plenary meeting of the ministers also decided to reject the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project for which Minister Snchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the Minister-President said that he did not agree with the arguments of the draft, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure measures through general standards for the public administration to prepare for them.
"I also do not think that if it did it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", and he recalled that planning public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, which has a constitutional mandate to run the state.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years and it translates into better exploitation of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing change, he argued, would be postponing the benefits of digitalisation which implies a public interest decision that has not only a technical dimension, "as it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues".
These issues, he stressed, "require the operation of a whole system established, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, encompassing a group of powers which the Constitution grants to the power of the State Executive".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition and they have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they have highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has in any way invaded the sphere of competence of Congress, since it ensures in the administrative sphere the respect of the laws issued by the Legislature, he assured.
The possibility of a vote-by-vote counting in Michoacn is being analysed
According to data highlighted by PREP, the difference between first and second place in the governor election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the total 6 74 minutes.
The possibility of "vote by vote" counting is a reality with regard to the electoral process this year in Michoacn, where according to data highlighted by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between first and second place in the election of the governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the total 6 74 minutes.
In this regard, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacn (IEM), Mara de los ngeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards with the federal electoral reform.
It will be recalled that Michoacn did not approve its Political Constitution, its State Electoral Code or its Electoral Justice Act, while the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the expiry of the legal deadline for this electoral process to take effect and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication within the deadlines set by the Official Gazette of the State Act, on the grounds that he had some objections.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and called the vote of the state representative for constitutional reforms "invalid and illegal", as he has no right to "sanction or challenge" them.
When asked about the possibility of "vote by vote", Mara de los ngeles Llanderal said that with the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the IEM it will be possible to carry out the partial and total counting of votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, it may be that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no voting record and count in the file of the ballot box is not with the president of it; or there are obvious errors or alterations of the minutes.
In addition, the total count of votes received at all polling stations may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the candidate presumed to have won the election and the candidate who came second in the poll is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition from the representative of the party and/or coalition that presented the second of the candidates reported.
The total count may also be carried out if, at the end of the joint count, the difference between the presumed winning candidate and the second-placed candidate is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express petition from the representative of the political party whose candidate came second, in which case the electoral packages which were partly counted shall be excluded.
It should be mentioned that this is the case in the Morelia election, where according to the PREP, the difference between first and second place is only 0.16 per cent, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
