The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has brought this country to the brink of economic disaster.
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with the President of Italy on Wednesday to introduce the new government that will face a crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic disaster and put the entire Eurozone at risk.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form the government.
He is expected to present a cabinet made up mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he would present the president with the results of his talks with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase", the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
"The picture is now well drawn", he added.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than usual, while Italy battled a political and financial crisis that pushed its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to restore the confidence in Italy that has been damaged.
Underlining the pressure on Monti to act quickly, market instability has put the yield on Italian 10-year BTP bonds above 7%, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be bailed out.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employers' group Confindustria, told the media after meeting with Monti: "We said we would be very supportive of this government".
We believe that this Government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency.
Monti's chances of success have been greatly boosted by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, which was forced to resign last Saturday by the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts will have a good result", Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told the press.
The support of the PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because until now many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti is forming.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could provoke a devastating new attack on the financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks added to the pressure by observing that a bankruptcy of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations with political parties, trade unions and employers' groups, as well as youth and women's organisations on Monday.
He'll finish his meeting tour on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, which enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief lull at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi was going to resign, the costs of Italy's debt have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty about the new prime minister's success.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 trillion euros, would be too much for the current financial defenses of the Eurozone.
Monti said his government should continue until the next elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before the elections are held.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that it should be formed only by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources have reported that mutual distrust and disagreements between parties make it difficult to try to include political figures.
