"Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In the exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to put on one of their best shows next Sunday at National Stadium.
They have waited more than 20 years, but the group assures that it will be a dream come true for them too to perform in this country.
That's what bassist and founding member Jeff Ament assured, speaking exclusively to Viva, from Brazil, last week.
The band is in the South American wing of their two-decade celebration tour and on Sunday 20th will make their only stop in Central America.
That day they will perform at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 p.m., alongside Los Angeles band The X and the Las Robertas Nationals.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which can be found in La Nacin on the Internet.
For his Costa Rican fans, the fact that Pearl Jam will perform in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has become a reality for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far it's been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once for my vacation; it's such a beautiful country and I think we can spend a few days there.
So it's exciting to bring our music there.
I'm asking you because there's a kind of devotion to the band, the fans live intensely in the days before.
What is your message to your most devoted followers?
Thank you for sticking by us all these years.
It took us 21 years to get to Costa Rica, so thank you for waiting so long, and we are sorry that it took so long to get to this concert.
Some people are already saying that his show is the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a little pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we've done in the last 21 years have been in the last two weeks.
We've had two huge shows in Sao Paolo and we hope that it's set us up for this concert in Costa Rica.
We're really looking forward to performing there.
We love this country, we love surfing and the jungle, and for both of those things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are amazing there.
My friends always went surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, right next to Mexico, are great places to surf; that's how we learned, through the guys who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, you were offered huge shows, with lots of songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never been there, we have no restrictions as to what we can do.
We're going to try to do the best show we can with a wide variety of songs, we're going to try to do two songs from each album and give our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never rehearse the repertoire.
Why is this?
I think partly because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, that's why it's very difficult to choose which songs to play each night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven't played for a very long time, it helps us to stay focused and surprises us because it reminds us why we loved those songs and that we may have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also becomes more interesting for people.
With this tour, you're celebrating 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe all you've accomplished?
Yes, I would.
First of all, I don't think either of us ever imagined that we were going to form a great rock band, and the fact that we've been doing it for over 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We keep talking about our blessings and the fact that we can continue to make music together is very exciting.
We love each other and we love making music.
We're lucky to be going to places in the world that we've always wanted to go.
Things couldn't have gone better for us.
What does it mean to you to have been a key part of the creation of grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this great group.
We're very close friends with the people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's surprising when a movement comes from a group of friends and it's unusual.
Occasionally, a group emerges from a city, but it's much stranger when five or ten groups emerge from the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we went to a festival with Alice in Chains and we went to Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we're lucky to still be friends with all of them and it's an honor for us to be part of that Seattle sound that has emerged.
It's also very strange that a group like yours has stayed together and with the same members for so long.
Yeah, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt joined us 13 years ago, and only that's a lot longer than most bands normally last.
First, I believe we're all lucky to be alive, and second, we all care about each other.
We're all close friends and thanks to that there are musical avenues that give freedom to everyone to experiment.
We have confidence in each other with each other's music and it couldn't get any better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy, but thanks to your success, you have been able to do what you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew older, it became easier for us to find balance.
We make sure that we don't spend too much time touring because it's easy to get caught up in this game of big crowds and people who like your music.
If we remember that people are there for music, it helps us not to forget that we have to respect music and what it has brought, without thinking about the fact that we are famous and a rock star, which is not really of interest to any of us.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote some good songs and at first it was great.
We were a band for almost three years and we didn't release a record until after Andy [Andrew Woods] died.
There was a lot of frustration that it was so short and the most important thing is that we're still very close friends with Bruce [Fairweather] and Greg [Gilmore] who started in the band with us and when I listen to a song or see a picture I think of the incredible person that Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to work, laugh, talk about music, football and many other things with him.
He was an amazing human being and we miss him.
The national band Las Robertas will open the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose her for the opening?
Yeah, the production sent us videos with different proposals and that was the band we liked the most, so we're excited to see what Las Robertas can offer live and it must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the lyrics to Yello Ledbetter live?
This is a question for Ed, so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he does it with the first words he imagines.
As a bass player, what are his influences?
There are so many...
The first ones I remember were Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski... and I was like, "What's going on?"
There's so many influences, I could talk all afternoon about the bass players I love.
How did Pearl Jam keep grunge going despite the fact that it's no longer in fashion?
I think we all feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I just mentioned, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the other bands that came out at the same time, and if it's relevant now, I think it's wonderful, because it's music that's worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are now making the best music ever.
At first, his music had a darker content and now it has become more positive.
What is behind this change?
It's interesting, because I think there are songs on the new album that seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe, that are described as very dark songs, even though these can sound a little bit positive.
With both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried when I listened to them and these are deeply dark songs.
I think that if you grow up and there's a trauma in your life and you lose a parent or a friend, those things start to affect your art and your music and these songs, no doubt, represent that to me.
I also think that you can be happy and even then you can make obscure music.
