Secretary Dionisio Prez Jcome gives details of the plane crash in which the Secretary of the Government, Francisco Blake, and seven others lost their lives
The Secretariat of Communications and Transport (SCT) informed that the results highlighted on the accident in which the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people lost their lives, indicate that the helicopter crashed directly into the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Prez Jcome, Secretary of Communications and Transportation, mentioned that before the aircraft took off, the pilot found that the weather conditions were adequate for flying.
"Elements that appear to indicate the unit had various ground contact, blades made contact with trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage".
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 persons, so it met the requirements necessary to transport the personnel.
He also said that investigations in the impact zone have not reported the appearance of any pieces on the ground.
"In one study it was reported that there are no parts or components of the aircraft in another location, the impact was structural.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers and met the requirements for carrying them.
The ground was inclined by seven to 30 degrees.
The Secretary has said that the priority is to get results as soon as possible, but the investigation may take a few months, or even a year.
Gilberto Lpez Meyer, general manager of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the impact, the Presidential Staff helicopter was operating at cruising speed and that it was on a soft upward ground.
"This information supports the hypothesis of a normal cruiser operation at the time of impact", he said.
During the press conference, the TSC holder, Prez Jcome, listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to aeronautical regulations, the flight was conducted in accordance with visual flight rules, which implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
Reports in the AICM mentioned adequate conditions for takeoff, and as the aircraft moved towards the border area between DF and the State of Mexico there were layers of low-altitude nebula.
Routes selected:
It is likely that because of the foggy conditions the crew sought a lower altitude and more visibility area towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last radar record of the aircraft coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a restricted area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact was on a straight and lateral trajectory.
The dispersion pattern of the aircraft debris suggests that the helicopter hit the ground under structural integrity conditions.
No sign of fire or explosion.
At the scene of the accident there is still no evidence of any kind of explosion or fire in the remains of the aircraft.
The latest investigation results indicate that the aircraft had multiple ground contact.
During the fieldwork, parts of the aircraft were found at an altitude of 9,200 feet above mean sea level, with the ground sloping from seven degrees to 30 degrees.
The photographs show the sequence in which it may have disintegrated along its journey.
The information provided seems to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After a thorough search of an area larger than the encircled area around the crash site, no scattered parts of the aircraft were found, supporting the presumption that the impact occurred under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS announces protocol to find the gene for obesity
Social Insurance is conducting an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people; this is supported by specialists from the IPN
The Mexican Social Insurance Institute (IMSS) announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in children and adolescents, called the 'Genetics of Childhood and Adolescent Obesity Protocol' which will allow for the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the Hospital of the Specialties of the National Medical Center of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz Lpez, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The investigation invites the public, whether eligible or not, to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de Mxico, where the underage tests are conducted every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He pointed out that the protocol started in the Cuauhtmoc Sports Unit (East Mexico State) and that from October 8, the activity takes place in the Nezahualcyolt Sports Unit (East Mexico State).
After reaching the target of 500 or 600 miners, the study will continue in the Unidad Sportiva Independencia (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Unidad Sportiva Morelos (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the aim of this investigation was to understand the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day is being celebrated on 14 November, he mentioned that the aim is to bring together three thousand children and young people aged between six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on diet.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family history of inherited diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturdays all participants will be subjected to anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetic (seeking to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz Lpez reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
"Health surveys in 1999 and 2006 reported a 77 percent increase in obesity among boys and 47 percent among girls in just six years, and a dramatic increase in overweight", said the IMSS specialist.
He stated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent of Indo-American heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African heritage and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetic cause of obesity is the inability to burn excess energy (calories), which is deposited as fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which allows detection of whether they are overweight or obese.
He even says that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the likelihood of suffering from metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is kept confidential, and the doctors give it in writing to the parents, who are told of each of the measures and changes in lifestyle they need to make to prevent disease.
Cruz Lpez explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the TV most of the day and using transportation instead of walking short distances.
Another cause is the high calorie intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales - cornmeal meat paste wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high fat and protein content and the genetics analysed in this protocol.
The asphalt of the UNAM would avoid the chassis
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at UNAM, develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better yield, regardless of environmental conditions and temperature
If the signals that the paved area were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200,000 paving stones each rainy season in the Valle de Mxico Metropolitan Area, warns Rafael Herrera Njera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the oil paved area is adequate, the paving stones could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A technological opinion on casings, organized in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing asphaltes modified with polymers to produce a mixture having similar characteristics to asphalt but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Njera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve yield and, consequently, the formation of the casings.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a combination of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a lower molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the paving stone its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of asphalt is that at high temperatures, almost 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it is almost solid, while at very low temperatures the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that the asphalt's strength on the streets is not uniform and changes during the day depending on environmental conditions and temperature, warns the chemical engineer.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de Mxico were mostly covered by a flexible paving, composed of six layers of material, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, which is made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the small stones that make up the bed, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it generating forces, it allows the forces to spread very well through the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, the chemical engineer thought, these would spread better.
"On top of the asphalt layer", he said, "you put a last layer called a rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand, which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide grip in the street.
As the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the effort, the bearing layer also requires that it be of adequate thickness and that the material from which it is made be maintained.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he says, as these affect the yield of the asphalt layer considerably.
When the soil gets wet, water is spread inside the layer and it is difficult for it to come out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and therefore causes the cuts.
In the process of forming a chassis, he says, the first thing that gets damaged is the rolling film and only later is the asphalt layer affected, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programmes.
The member of the National Research System explained that vehicle load is another important factor for chassis formation and therefore the thickness of each pavement layer must always be related to vehicle load and ensure its satisfaction, to avoid frequent chassis formation.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow the chassis to be repaired easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
