Early in his career, Gonzlez worked in the municipalities of Choc, where he often had to spend more than five days in the forest to reach the location where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he was transferred to the capital of Valle and after taking adequate courses, he specialized in fingerprinting, which is the study of the skin of friction, that is, the palms and feet.
During the week of the operation on alias Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew he had to identify two bodies and one of them was suspected to be that of the man who led the world's oldest guerrilla warfare, so he was asked to take the map with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo Len Senz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigative team at the scene of the body, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, as it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a local farmer, no glasses, and much thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
With a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a scraper, and a flashlight, Eleazar compared the fingerprints on the corpse with those on the map.
His eye did not deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the official who confirmed to Defense Minister Juan Carlos Pinzn that yes, he was the supreme leader of the FARC.
