A Russian scientist helped Iran 's nuclear program
A Russian scientist, Vycheslav Danilenko, has helped Iran develop a detonator that could be used with a nuclear weapon, a U.S. NGO specializing in nuclear risk claimed Monday.
The Institute for International Science and Security (ISIS) relies on the recent report of the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and other documents from that UN agency to identify this researcher.
The IAEA expressed last week its "serious concerns" about a "possible military dimension" of Iran's nuclear programme.
According to ISIS, drawing heavily on IAEA documents, Mr Danilenko, born in 1934, worked for three decades from the 1960s at a Soviet military nuclear facility in Chelyabinsk (Ural), and was allegedly involved in the manufacture of synthetic diamonds by blasting.
In 1989 or 1991, he left the center to establish a company producing "nano-diamonds" in Kiev.
The economic difficulties of his company would have led him to contact the Iranian embassy in Ukraine in 1995.
He is alleged to have subsequently cooperated in the Iranian programme from 1996 to 2002, before returning to Russia.
In its latest report, the IAEA cites "strong indications that Iran's development" of a nuclear detonation system "was aided by the work of a foreign expert, who not only was well versed in this technique but who, as one Member State informed the Agency, worked for most of his career on this technology within the military nuclear programme of his home country".
Anti-Muslim crimes and offenses increased by 50%
Crimes and crimes against Muslims increased by nearly 50 percent from 2009 to 2010, while other racial and religious violence decreased slightly or not much, according to FBI statistics released Monday.
According to these figures, the total number of violent crimes against Muslims increased from 107 in 2009 to 160 in 2010, a 49% increase, while the number of crimes against Catholics increased by 13%, the number of crimes against Jews decreased by 4%, and the overall number of anti-religious crimes and offenses increased by 14%.
The total number of "hate crimes" rose very slightly to 6,628, with 47.3 percent of them motivated by racial differences and 20 percent by religious differences, according to the FBI.
"After a decline in 2009, it is disturbing to see these crimes and offenses increase again", Human Rights First said, "the increase in anti-Muslim violence is particularly significant", the organization added in a statement.
"Human Rights First has long stressed that violence against Muslims, as well as all forms of hate crimes, must be considered a serious violation of human rights", adds Paul Legendre, a senior member of the organization.
"The US government can and must do more to tackle these abuses", he added, saying that this could include improving police reporting on "hate crimes".
The "hate crime" in US federal law is a legacy of the civil rights era.
This legislation was passed after the death of Martin Luther King to punish violence based on race, color, religion, origin and now sexual orientation.
