Austria
The budgetary "golden rule" is inscribed in the Constitution
The Social Democratic/Christian Democratic government in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to include in the constitution a "golden rule" on the budget to reduce government deficits and thus avoid a possible downgrading by rating agencies of Austria's sovereign rating (triple A).
The Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann himself announced this decision at a ministerial meeting, when Austria's public debt stood at 74.6%, well above the 60% ceiling set by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece and Spain.
"If Austria's creditworthiness were reduced by just one step, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion euros more in interest every year", argued the Christian Democrat Vice Chancellor and Minister for Foreign Affairs, Michael Spindelegger.
Austria is thus following up on a request made at the Brussels summit of euro area countries on 26 October: the Heads of State and Government had then demanded that the reduction of public deficits and a return to balance of public accounts be included in the constitution or in a law of equal value by the end of 2012.
The Austrian government's approach is similar to the German model, since Germany was the first European country to adopt such a rule.
By 2017, the structural government deficit will have to decrease by 0,75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year and, from 2017, the structural government deficit of the federal state will not have to exceed 0,35% of GDP each year, while the regional states and municipalities will have to present balanced budgets.
The objective is to bring the public debt under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/21.
The strong yen
Noda threatens new intervention in the foreign exchange market
Japanese Prime Minister Yoshihiko Noda warned on Tuesday that Japanese authorities would intervene again in the foreign exchange market if the yen continued to rise.
"We will intervene as we did last time if we find excessive volatility" in the yen exchange rate, Mr Noda explained to the Senate.
On Tuesday, the yen was close to the historic levels that prompted the Japanese authorities to intervene on 31 October.
On that day, Tokyo sold heavily in yen against dollars to lower the value of the Japanese currency, which had just set a new record since 1945 against the greenback.
But the yen has been steadily rising since then, fuelled by purchases by investors who see it as a 'safe haven' in these uncertain times of global economic slowdown and European debt crisis.
The dollar fell below 77 yen on Tuesday and the euro fell below the symbolic bar of 105 yen, close to the levels that triggered the last intervention.
Before the financial crisis of 2008-2009, the dollar was worth around 120 yen and the euro more than 160 yen.
This surge in the Japanese currency is hurting the archipelago's exports as it increases the cost of Made in Japan products and reduces the value of foreign income earned by Japanese firms when they convert it into national currency.
"Japan is struggling to rebuild" since the March 11 earthquake and tsunami that devastated the northeastern Tohoku region, said Noda, who fears that the rising yen will kill the fragile recovery.
The world's third-largest economy returned to growth in the third quarter - 1.5% compared with the previous quarter - for the first time in a year, thanks to a rebound in exports and household consumption hit by the disaster.
But the prime minister felt that the rising yen did not reflect "Japan's economic fundamentals".
Finance Minister Jun Azumi called on the Bank of Japan (BoJ), which opened a two-day meeting of its monetary policy council on Tuesday, to take all possible measures to weaken the yen.
But the institution's deputy governor, Hirohide Yamaguchi, warned that the BoJ had already taken "appropriate measures", suggesting that no further monetary easing was to be expected until Wednesday.
At its last meeting in late October, the issuer increased its purchases of Treasury bills by 5,000 billion yen ($47 billion), raising the cap on the amount it spends on purchases of various financial securities to 55,000 billion yen ($519 billion) to flood the market with liquidity.
