Energy policy:
The facts must prevail over the dogmas
If there is one subject which cannot be dealt with from a short-term perspective or under the influence of emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of firms.
It is a healthy thing for an election to be an occasion to reflect on such issues and the place of nuclear energy in them.
The debate will only be successful if it explores the full range of economic, social and environmental consequences of the options proposed.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
With 7 billion people on the planet, population change will double the demand for electricity by 2050, unless we deprive a huge portion of the world's population of a vital element.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil fuels will have to be mitigated in order to continue to produce electricity on a permanent basis, not to mention the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, a topic which has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Germany therefore remains isolated in its decision to abandon nuclear power.
This is not the case for Belgium, which is subjecting its own to the need to be able to find a replacement source capable of replacing itself, or for Switzerland, which is simply intending to build only the latest generation of power stations.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name a few, are pursuing their projects with determination.
The United States, meanwhile, decided after Fukushima to add a unit to its fleet by resuming construction of a power plant that had been halted after the Three Mile Island accident.
The German renewable energy model is sometimes cited as an example, but the reality is quite different.
The choice of Berlin will result in higher electricity prices, energy dependence aggravated by increased use of imported gas, particularly from Russia, and a jump in CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal power stations.
Within a few months, all these unpleasant effects are already being felt.
The case of Denmark is worth considering.
Europe's wind champion, it gets 30% of its electricity from it, it is also one of the biggest users of coal and gas due to the intermittence of wind; as a result, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to our consistent energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining the industrial tool on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
The Commission has not yet decided whether to accept the proposal for a directive on the protection of the environment.
This is a price which the vast majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not oppose this energy in principle, as polls show.
We should recall that the energy policy of our country has made it possible to build an industrial sector with 125 000 direct jobs and 410 000 induced jobs.
It is a strong exporter and it brings in a galaxy of SMEs specialising in international markets and makes them very creative in non-localised jobs.
If France were to decide to leave nuclear power, it would be sacrificing many of these SMEs by reducing the 6 billion a year of French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician would order an EPR designed to run for 60 years when the decline of its manufacturer is programmed?
To solve the energy equation, we must admit that there is no miracle source of electricity, nor is there any diabolical one.
Areva's development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions is a testament to the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
We have a safety authority in France which exercises strict and transparent control over the existing power stations and the Flamanville site.
Our teams, which are renowned for their professionalism, are equally obsessed with safety.
In the last half century, the nuclear industry has suffered three major accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, was operated under normal operating conditions and had no human or environmental consequences.
At Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human mistakes caused the tragedy.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident is the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that have caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did from the two previous ones.
As a result of this approach and cooperation between the safety authorities, operators and French and German manufacturers, the EPR is designed to withstand such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians who wish to build a power station, the halting of its construction in Flamanville would be a magnificent gift to Areva and EDF's competitors by leaving them the free way to take the lead in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy package for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogma and partisan maneuvers dominate a debate so decisive for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy of Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - overcrowding of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of the number, compatibility of this policy with France's self-proclaimed status as a "human rights country".
More recently, the issue of administrative harassment of foreign students has made headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see Liberation of 23 May) declaring that France "does not need foreign talent, masons and restaurant waiters".
But it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
It's that there's a pretty broad consensus on this between the left and the right.
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac, who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed people should not be a problem in a country with nearly 2 million immigrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard, who explained that France "cannot accept all the misery in the world" in 1990.
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared by both left and right.
On both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity shown to immigrants.
In his programme, Franois Hollande confines himself to trivia, saying that co-development will solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electoral; but it is economically very costly.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent book summarizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among scholars on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that receive immigrants.
Restricting immigration anemize growth and harm jobs.
Fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they may replace domestic workers, especially the low-skilled, putting downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that in reality immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national workers, mainly working in sectors with a shortage of jobs.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors which do not attract domestic workers, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not follow the supply of jobs.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon will have difficulty working in a country with a shortage of anaesthetists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants mean that the arrival of immigrants has a positive effect on the salaries and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri has calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows leads to an increase in real wages of between 0.6 and 0.9% in the long term.
This is without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (a large proportion of naturalized immigrants among US Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, on average accounting for 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organisation, for example, estimates that in Germany, an immigrant who reaches the age of 30 will contribute a net contribution (revenue minus expenditure) of EUR 150000 to the public budget on average over his entire life.
At the beginning of his term, Mr Sarkozy wanted to go "with the teeth" to find the missing points of growth.
The teeth in question, used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, but we have to think about European democracy
Democracy is a precious asset; it is also a fragile asset.
The European continent should be able to remember it, for having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, it has experienced throughout the 20th century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have thought that it would be sufficient for democracy to triumph over its enemies once and for all if it exercised its right to vote, and to do so in the most direct way possible.
We have known since Napoleon the Little that this was a thought-provoking thing to do.
Universal suffrage, if it is the necessary condition for democracy, is not the sufficient condition and can even become an "instrument of oppression" as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of powers, education, enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis in Europe we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is also and above all a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum has been a double-revealer in this respect: that of the need for a powerful return to politics, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought through to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have now shifted, and for many of them, the Republican soldiers are no longer firing in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain by demanding a succession of national referendums, organised as needed and in a dispersed order.
A whitewash for the absolute European monarch or a leap into the void of nationalist retreat: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want to have a coup, but we want a common, full-fledged, peaceful and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - you wouldn't know where to stop listing them - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that is bending to the dictates of the markets and the rating agencies, suffering from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is humiliated on the international stage.
There is concern about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe - but it is Europe as a whole which is slowly losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to give back to the people's sovereignty the control of the European project.
Because together, Europeans can reduce their debt burden, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The way out of the crisis will require decisions at European level which cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, unless, of course, they lead to disaster.
After long fighting this proposal of the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for a European economic government.
Well, that's one thing.
But to think of it without stronger political and democratic integration, and experienced as such by the citizens, would be a new folly and a new dead end.
We must take a new step in the European construction.
To make the Republic in France, we had to "make" Republicans.
The Revolution in the interests could not do this.
That lesson still holds true.
We must build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be achieved by building a more democratic Europe politically, a true European people's sovereignty.
To make Europe, let's make people from Europe.
Contactless smart cards are becoming more common
The world smart card exhibition opens on Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, in an optimistic climate.
The year 2011 should end with an 11% increase in global sales of microprocessor cards (bank cards, SIM-card phones, etc.) to more than 6 billion units, according to Eurosmart.
