The world according to the Republican presidential candidates
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry compete with simplicity and ignorance.
Can an America weakened by the crisis manage a complex world with simple, even simplistic ideas?
Listening to the Republican presidential candidates, voters might believe it.
In recent days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and others have been making a number of thunderous statements and abbreviations on foreign policy, traditionally a Republican stronghold.
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, slogans - often unsupported - were chanted.
Mitt Romney, the top contender for the nomination from the "Grand Old Party", threatened to drag the Chinese to the WTO and charge them "for manipulating their currency", a prominent theme in an America angered by the migration of entire sectors of its industry to Asia.
He said that it was too bad that it would involve the outbreak of a trade war.
