Nord Stream, the new gateway for Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Western Europe directly to Russia via the Baltic Sea, has been put into operation.
It must supply the equivalent of 30 million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with a bang.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended, on the shores of the Baltic Sea, last Tuesday, with orchestra and a fine buffet, the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia to Germany under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Franois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have together turned the steering wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western European grid.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas will be delivered to Western Europe each year via a first 1,224-km pipeline linking the St. Petersburg region with the Mecklenburg-Pomerania state.
A second pipeline is due to be completed by the end of 2012, delivering a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And there is already talk of building a third on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction project looks like a victory.
The project had been strongly opposed by Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, both countries are losing some of their power: it is becoming more difficult for them to exert pressure on Russia by threatening to close off its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But this is at the cost of a weakened energy Europe, since the project has created a rift between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in fulfilling its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavy gas consumers and whose deposits are in decline.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically", said Franois Fillon, demonstrating how political and economic the major gas contracts are.
All this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom executives, who were in large numbers at the Lubmin gas arrivals.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The submarine tube is made of steel with concrete to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It lies on the seabed, at an average of 200 metres.
The construction of the new building was to avoid the World War II minefields.
"About 100 had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution", says Jens Mller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
Measures to protect wildlife have also been increased.
The tube is a long metal snake, as heavy as 242 Eiffel Towers, and nothing interrupts it along its entire length: no valve, no maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off Sweden, but the project was abandoned as the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state-owned company permanently established off their coast.
"In the event of a breakdown, we stop the gas flowing in less than a minute", explains Jens Mller.
If the gas leaks, the gas in the pipeline leaks into the air.
But this is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have planned the welds to leak every 100,000 years.
The status of the pipeline is monitored by a submarine robot, towed by a ship, for outside observation, and by a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
It is shaped like a cigar and is inserted into the tube, which is one meter wide and is pushed by the gas.
When it arrives, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it delivers precise information on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to run for 50 years without any repair.
The gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
It's 200 bars at the start, and 100 bars at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which retains 51% of the shares.
The German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), the Dutch Gasunie and the French GDF Suez group (9% each) joined them.
These five companies have set up a joint venture, Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where the taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company, for a renewable period of 20 years, all gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported", says Jens Mller.
The construction of the pipeline was financed 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for both pipes.
For example, the investment for GDF Suez amounted to 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are sure to get their money's worth, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea at Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
The gas is released through a four-and-a-half-meter-high valve.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specifics of the incoming gas before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and by 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand name notebook.
Created some 15 years ago by an Italian company, the Moleskine aims to restore the taste for writing.
It smells like adventure, hours spent writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its broken white-colored leaves, as if aged by time.
Yet the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, was responsible for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is based on an ancient production technique, mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton used to cover benches, for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travelers.
"Moleskine brought back to life an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century", says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million units.
We are far from the secret production of the early years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond Italian borders and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish a robot portrait of the buyer, since the notebook appeals to businessmen, students and professionals alike.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which started with 12 employees, has grown to almost 100 today and has since 2008 two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in bookstores, from Fnac to small shops in the city centre and has managed to impose her identity.
"We have followed the tide of time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of e-mail", explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebooks.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover for the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products: bags, diaries, pens, computer covers... The brand is available on a wide range of media.
A success that made people envious: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers so high?
Approximately 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
The 15th week for disabled employment opens today.
Despite a voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for disabled people is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared to 9% for the general population.
Discouraging ?
"No", says Eric Blanchet, executive director of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for employment for the disabled.
"The progress made in the last 15 years is remarkable".
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice as high as it is now, but three times as high".
"There is still a lot of work to be done".
It must be said that for the unemployed disabled, there are still many obstacles to access to employment.
They are rather elderly: 37% are over 50 years old (average 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a baccalaureate and out of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10 000 are disabled.
Finally, longterm unemployment is widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
In short, all these criteria make it particularly difficult to return to work, and "are the root of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, managing director of Tremplin, an association set up in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
That's for the objective brakes.
It is not to be said that the mentality is changing, but too slowly.
A survey carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cit association indicated that the managers interviewed had "a low level of knowledge of disability", with "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, with mental or intellectual disabilities".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the 6% employment target of disabled workers, set in a law of... 1987.
The latest known figures, from 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now at around 3%", says Pierre Blanc, director-general of the Agence de la Fdration des Finances Internationales (Agefiph), the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with the law.
The number of 'taxed' establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created a lot of pressure on companies", explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups".
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
Hazard: "How happy are you"
Before facing the Blues on Tuesday night (20:45), Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens did not hide the pleasure they are getting from this friendly match.
It is not even written that there was collusion between them, but the picture is symbolic.
Sitting side by side on the stage of the Stade de France auditorium, Georges Leekens and Eden Hazard made peace.
Five months after his striker's mood gesture against Turkey, the Belgian coach has nothing but praise to say about him.
"I'm very happy with Eden, his progress and the fact that he's Belgian".
"I want to move on", says the Lillois.
As for the contrast between his performances at club and national team, "it's a whole, he justified himself".
"In Lille I am there all year round, which is not the case in Belgium".
"I have to get my marks".
Scheduled for Friday night's match against Romania and France, Hazard is coming to Saint-Denis to finally shine.
But not without the notion of "pleasure".
The Blues, he's been cheering them on since he was seven and the winning campaigns of 1998 and 2000.
"I've always been tolerant", he says.
This will certainly help to reinforce the "private" character of this meeting.
Especially since in front, "there are Mathieu (Debuchy), Yohan (Cabaye) and Adil (Rami) ", he recalls.
"We just ran into each other".
"To be able to play against them, it's just happiness!"
Leekens, for his part, has spoken of "pride".
"Pride" to play "a gala game".
"Proud" also to see - as a "neighbour" - that France has "become a very high-level team again" a little over a year after the trauma of Knysna.
"Laurent Blanc has done a great job", he said, excited.
While Belgium will miss the next Euro, the technician would be happy to share the plane with the Blues heading... Brazil in 2014.
"Our little Belgians are growing up", he said.
"We're building something, the players are ambitious, they're hungry".
"You'll find out in the next few games", including the one against France.
Portugal is very confident
Paulo Bento's Portugal is starting with much optimism its relegation play-off against Bosnia at 22:00 on Tuesday in Lisbon.
At first, both teams lacked realism.
"At the end of those 90 minutes, we'll be a happy team and, most importantly, a happy country".
Paulo Bento is already doing it in Poland and Ukraine.
For him, there is no doubt that the Selecao, which he has been in charge of since September 2010, will qualify for Euro 2012.
Portugal is indeed only 90 minutes from happiness.
But there is one game to play, and one opponent, Bosnia, to beat.
After the 0-0 draw on Friday in Zenica, it's clear that the games are not over.
Portugal dominated the game for over an hour, but they were unable to score the valuable goal that would have relieved them.
"It's a good result, but there's a risk because we didn't score on the outside".
But at home, in their bright Luz Stadium in Lisbon, the Portuguese are convinced to pass, in front of an audience that should be there as hot, even though the game is obviously "very tight", says an optimistic but lucid Bento.
"We expect a very close game, but we are absolutely convinced that we can take the lead", said the 42-year-old Portuguese coach.
"We still have a 50% chance of being at Euro 2012", said Carlos Queiroz's successor.
The draw reported on Friday from Bosnia forces the Portuguese to score and win.
One draw can be enough for the Bosnians, who also need to score.
"It's a good result, but it's a bit risky because we didn't score outside", Bento regrets.
"We are going to play against a team that has a lot of technical qualities and has players with a lot of individual qualities", he added.
As in Zenica, the Portuguese intend to put maximum pressure on the Bosnians to "not give them time to think".
Good idea, provided you're realistic this time.
